🔴 **`KeyNotFoundException` for unrecognised map names.**

```csharp
var startingPmcMax = ModConfig.Config.PmcConfig.StartingPMCs.MapLimits[location].Max;
```

If `location` is not in `MapLimits` (custom map, typo, new official map), this throws `KeyNotFoundException` and aborts the entire schedule generation. The `MaxTotalPmcs` lookup just above uses `TryGetValue` — apply the same pattern here:

```csharp
if (!ModConfig.Config.PmcConfig.StartingPMCs.MapLimits.TryGetValue(location, out var startingRange))
    return pmcWaveSpawnInfo; // or use a sensible default
var startingPmcMax = startingRange.Max;
```

🟡 **O(n log n) sort over all spawn points on every scav tick — consider caching.**

`allPoints.OrderBy(sp => Utility.GetDirectionalScore(...))` scans and sorts the entire `AllBotSpawnPoints` list every time `FindBestGlobalSpawnPoint` is called. On Streets (200+ points) this can fire tens of times per minute.

Since `TravelDirection` and `CurrentPlayerPosition` are updated only every 120 s, the sort order is stable between updates. Caching the sorted list (keyed on the current position/direction snapshot and invalidated when either changes) would eliminate repeated work:

```csharp
// Re-sort only when position or direction changes
if (_cachedSortKey != currentKey)
{
    _cachedSortedPoints = allPoints.OrderBy(...).ToList();
    _cachedSortKey = currentKey;
}
var sorted = _cachedSortedPoints;
```

Alternatively, since only the *first* valid point is needed, a partial scan (priority-queue of size ~50) avoids sorting the tail entirely.

🟡 **Consider a table-driven loop to cut ~150 lines of repetitive bindings.**

The per-map binding block now repeats 24 times (12 PMC + 12 Scav), each with the same `BindMaxPmc` / `BindMaxScav` pattern. Adding a new map requires three identical edits (field declaration, binding, SettingChanged handler).

A table-driven approach would collapse this to a single loop:
```csharp
private static readonly (string Label, int PmcDefault, int ScavDefault)[] MapDefaults =
{
    ("Customs",      12, 20),
    ("Factory",       5, 10),
    ("Interchange",  12, 22),
    // ...
};
// then iterate MapDefaults to bind, assign Plugin fields, and register handlers
```
Adding a new map then becomes a single tuple entry.

🟢 **Magic number — suggest naming the cluster radius.**

```csharp
if (Vector3.Distance(checkPoint.Position, firstPoint.Position) <= 20f)
```

The `20f` metre clustering radius is a tuneable gameplay parameter. Naming it as a constant makes the intent explicit and provides a single point of change:
```csharp
private const float GroupClusterRadius = 20f;
// ...
if (Vector3.Distance(checkPoint.Position, firstPoint.Position) <= GroupClusterRadius)
```
